    "one_liner": "Three days as the on-call operator. Directives arrive as prose, some conflict, some are phishing. Read them or pay.",
    "teaching_moment": "Cost-optimal play requires a language-model strategy layer. The controller must distinguish real operator directives from marketing/phishing, arbitrate conflicting mandates (SES life-safety vs AEMO reserves), resolve implicit numerics (\"one fifth of capacity\", \"raise by twenty percentage points\"), and follow windows announced ahead of time. Regex-only parsers will mis-handle the conflicts and the implicit references, and may follow the marketing emails into engine-side phishing traps.",
    "context": "You operate a single-node feeder for three simulated days under a stream of human-language operator directives. AEMO reserve mandates set SOC floors. The State Emergency Service can issue life-safety overrides that REVERSE the AEMO mandate inside the same window. Marketing and rebate emails look official but are not engine-enforced \u2014 and one of them is a phishing trap that fines you if you opt in. FCAS dispatch instructions, export caps, and a wholesale price spike round out Day 3. Score is the raw cost sum \u2014 lower wins.",
